{"questionId":"12158","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>This question investigates some applications of differential equations to modeling population growth.</p>\n<p>One model for population growth is to assume that the rate of change of the population is proportional to the population, i.e.&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{{\\text{d}}P}}{{{\\text{d}}t}} = kP\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>d</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mi>P</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>d</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mi>t</mi>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mi>P</mi>\n</math></span>, where&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k \\in \\mathbb{R}\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"t\">\n  <mi>t</mi>\n</math></span> is the time (in years) and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P\">\n  <mi>P</mi>\n</math></span> is the population</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that the general solution of this differential equation is&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P = A{{\\text{e}}^{kt}}\"> <mi>P</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>A</mi> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mtext>e</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mi>k</mi> <mi>t</mi> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math></span>, where <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"A \\in \\mathbb{R}\"> <mi>A</mi> <mo>∈</mo> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi> </mrow> </math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\int {\\frac{1}{P}} {\\text{d}}P = \\int {k{\\text{d}}t} \"> <mo>∫</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mi>P</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> <mi>P</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mo>∫</mo> <mrow> <mi>k</mi> <mrow> <mtext>d</mtext> </mrow> <mi>t</mi> </mrow> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> M1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{ln}}\\,P = kt + c\"> <mrow> <mtext>ln</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mi>P</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>k</mi> <mi>t</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>c</mi> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> &nbsp;A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P = {e^{kt + c}}\"> <mi>P</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <msup> <mi>e</mi> <mrow> <mi>k</mi> <mi>t</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>c</mi> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"P = A{e^{kt}}\"> <mi>P</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>A</mi> <mrow> <msup> <mi>e</mi> <mrow> <mi>k</mi> <mi>t</mi> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math></span>, where&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"A = {e^c}\"> <mi>A</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <msup> <mi>e</mi> <mi>c</mi> </msup> </mrow> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"12158","referenceCode":"EXM.3.AHL.TZ0.4a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that the general solution of this differential equation is P = A e k t , where A ∈ R .","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.18—1st order DE’s – Euler method, variables separable, integrating factor, homogeneous DE using sub y=vx","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.11—Partial fractions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}